        },
        "thread_ts": "1576932369.039500",
        "parent_user_id": "U5STGTB3J",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "qos\/",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "With your third article I discovered the category approach in linguistics. And it is interesting to draw a parallel with programming. At least knowing that our mind is a kind of \"catorygizer\" is helpful in designing tools for thoughts and especially for building those tools with programming."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "user": "UJ6LDMMN0",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1577102893.055000",
        "edited": {
            "user": "UJ6LDMMN0",
            "ts": "1577103020.000000"
        },
        "client_msg_id": "c8222a6c-da99-4b7f-8b76-9329127c920e",
        "text": "And if you read French, I recommand this book by *Gilles Dowek* (a french computer scientist and philosopher) : *\"Ce dont on ne peut parler, il faut l’écrire\"*. Let me try to translate the title: \"what you can't tell by speaking you have to tell by writing\" (hope it is close enough to te Dowek idea!).\n\nIt is a very interesting book wich compares natural languages to other languages. In fact in French we have two separate words: \"langues\" are natural languages (English, French...) and \"languages\" are all other languages (math notations, music scores, programming languages...).\n\nNatural languages were first spoken before written, and others were create to write stuff that benefit in expressivness when written. In fact writing was \"invented\" not to write down what humans were talking about, but to count things, it was a very utilitarian use. It helped us a lot in the action of counting and doing business.\n\nI found very inspiring the separation of the two kinds of languages, and what is different and similar.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "0c210ee2df74",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2021-11-13\/2722434855730_0c210ee2df74838f8683_72.png",
            "first_name": "nicolas",
            "real_name": "nicolas decoster",
            "display_name": "ogadaki",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "nicolas.decoster",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1576932369.039500",
        "parent_user_id": "U5STGTB3J",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "Sxc",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "And if you read French, I recommand this book by "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Gilles Dowek",
                                "style": {
                                    "bold": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " (a french computer scientist and philosopher) : "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\"Ce dont on ne peut parler, il faut l’écrire\"",
                                "style": {
                                    "bold": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ". Let me try to translate the title: \"what you can't tell by speaking you have to tell by writing\" (hope it is close enough to te Dowek idea!).\n\nIt is a very interesting book wich compares natural languages to other languages. In fact in French we have two separate words: \"langues\" are natural languages (English, French...) and \"languages\" are all other languages (math notations, music scores, programming languages...).\n\nNatural languages were first spoken before written, and others were create to write stuff that benefit in expressivness when written. In fact writing was \"invented\" not to write down what humans were talking about, but to count things, it was a very utilitarian use. It helped us a lot in the action of counting and doing business.\n\nI found very inspiring the separation of the two kinds of languages, and what is different and similar."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
